            <p style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 16px;">
                <strong>The 1,123 cap serves three strategic purposes:</strong>
            </p>
            <ol style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 1.8; margin-left: 24px;">
                <li><strong>Data quality:</strong> Insurance companies adjust settlement tactics by region. We need diverse national data (not just California/Florida). State-based allocation ensures comprehensive coverage across all 50 states.</li>
                <li><strong>Credibility:</strong> 1,123 is specific, not rounded — it signals this is a real allocation, not marketing. Each state's allocation is proportional to its PI attorney population.</li>
                <li><strong>Fair distribution:</strong> Without caps, California and Florida would dominate (200+ members each), leaving rural states with zero representation. State caps ensure every region contributes and benefits.</li>
            </ol>
            <p style="font-size: 16pt; line-height: 1.8; margin-top: 16px;">
                <strong>Why not county-level?</strong> Too granular — small counties wouldn't fill spots. State-level balances urgency with realistic fill rates.
